195 class Series(base.IndexOpsMixin, generic.NDFrame):
196 """
197 One-dimensional ndarray with axis labels (including time series).
198  
199 Labels need not be unique but must be a hashable type. The object
200 supports both integer- and label-based indexing and provides a host of
201 methods for performing operations involving the index. Statistical
202 methods from ndarray have been overridden to automatically exclude
203 missing data (currently represented as NaN).
204  
205 Operations between Series (+, -, /, *, **) align values based on their
206 associated index values-- they need not be the same length. The result
207 index will be the sorted union of the two indexes.
208  
209 Parameters
210 ----------
211 data : array-like, Iterable, dict, or scalar value
212 Contains data stored in Series. If data is a dict, argument order is
213 maintained.
214 index : array-like or Index (1d)
215 Values must be hashable and have the same length as `data`.
216 Non-unique index values are allowed. Will default to
217 RangeIndex (0, 1, 2, ..., n) if not provided. If data is dict-like
  • E501 Line too long (82 > 79 characters)
218 and index is None, then the keys in the data are used as the index. If the
  • E501 Line too long (83 > 79 characters)
219 index is not None, the resulting Series is reindexed with the index values.
220 dtype : str, numpy.dtype, or ExtensionDtype, optional
221 Data type for the output Series. If not specified, this will be
222 inferred from `data`.
223 See the :ref:`user guide <basics.dtypes>` for more usages.
224 name : str, optional
225 The name to give to the Series.
226 copy : bool, default False
227 Copy input data. Only affects Series or 1d ndarray input. See examples.
228  
229 Examples
230 --------
231 Constructing Series from a dictionary with an Index specified
232  
233 >>> d = {'a': 1, 'b': 2, 'c': 3}
234 >>> ser = pd.Series(data=d, index=['a', 'b', 'c'])
235 >>> ser
236 a 1
237 b 2
238 c 3
239 dtype: int64
240  
241 The keys of the dictionary match with the Index values, hence the Index
242 values have no effect.
243  
244 >>> d = {'a': 1, 'b': 2, 'c': 3}
245 >>> ser = pd.Series(data=d, index=['x', 'y', 'z'])
246 >>> ser
247 x NaN
248 y NaN
249 z NaN
250 dtype: float64
251  
252 Note that the Index is first build with the keys from the dictionary.
253 After this the Series is reindexed with the given Index values, hence we
254 get all NaN as a result.
255  
256 Constructing Series from a list with `copy=False`.
257  
258 >>> r = [1, 2]
259 >>> ser = pd.Series(r, copy=False)
260 >>> ser.iloc[0] = 999
261 >>> r
262 [1, 2]
263 >>> ser
264 0 999
265 1 2
266 dtype: int64
267  
268 Due to input data type the Series has a `copy` of
269 the original data even though `copy=False`, so
270 the data is unchanged.
271  
272 Constructing Series from a 1d ndarray with `copy=False`.
273  
274 >>> r = np.array([1, 2])
275 >>> ser = pd.Series(r, copy=False)
276 >>> ser.iloc[0] = 999
277 >>> r
278 array([999, 2])
279 >>> ser
280 0 999
281 1 2
282 dtype: int64
283  
284 Due to input data type the Series has a `view` on
285 the original data, so
286 the data is changed as well.
287 """

736 def view(self, dtype: Dtype | None = None) -> Series:
737 """
738 Create a new view of the Series.
739  
740 This function will return a new Series with a view of the same
741 underlying values in memory, optionally reinterpreted with a new data
742 type. The new data type must preserve the same size in bytes as to not
743 cause index misalignment.
744  
745 Parameters
746 ----------
747 dtype : data type
748 Data type object or one of their string representations.
749  
750 Returns
751 -------
752 Series
753 A new Series object as a view of the same data in memory.
754  
755 See Also
756 --------
757 numpy.ndarray.view : Equivalent numpy function to create a new view of
758 the same data in memory.
759  
760 Notes
761 -----
762 Series are instantiated with ``dtype=float64`` by default. While
763 ``numpy.ndarray.view()`` will return a view with the same data type as
764 the original array, ``Series.view()`` (without specified dtype)
765 will try using ``float64`` and may fail if the original data type size
766 in bytes is not the same.
767  
768 Examples
769 --------
770 >>> s = pd.Series([-2, -1, 0, 1, 2], dtype='int8')
771 >>> s
772 0 -2
773 1 -1
774 2 0
775 3 1
776 4 2
777 dtype: int8
778  
779 The 8 bit signed integer representation of `-1` is `0b11111111`, but
780 the same bytes represent 255 if read as an 8 bit unsigned integer:
781  
782 >>> us = s.view('uint8')
783 >>> us
784 0 254
785 1 255
786 2 0
787 3 1
788 4 2
789 dtype: uint8
790  
791 The views share the same underlying values:
792  
793 >>> us[0] = 128
794 >>> s
795 0 -128
796 1 -1
797 2 0
798 3 1
799 4 2
800 dtype: int8
801 """
802 return self._constructor(
803 self._values.view(dtype), index=self.index
804 ).__finalize__(self, method="view")
